Cars4U Project¶

Objective:¶

1.Explore and visualize the dataset.

2.Build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars.

3.Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Data:¶

1.S.No. : Serial Number

2.Name : Name of the car which includes Brand name and Model name

3.Location : The location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase Cities

4.Year : Manufacturing year of the car

5.Kilometers_driven : The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in KM.

6.Fuel_Type : The type of fuel used by the car. (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)

7.Transmission : The type of transmission used by the car. (Automatic / Manual)

8.Owner : Type of ownership

9.Mileage : The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg

10.Engine : The displacement volume of the engine in CC.

11.Power : The maximum power of the engine in bhp.

12.Seats : The number of seats in the car.

13.New_Price : The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs.(1 Lakh = 100, 000)

14.Price : The price of the used car in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh = 100, 000)

Data Pre-processing¶

Observations on Mileage¶

The car mileage has two units, km/kg and kmpl.

The cars have 2 different types of fuel.

Diesel cars km/kg (kilometers per kg) is use LPG and CNG based engines, and kmpl(kilometers per liter) is use petrol and

Now we can check fuel type in our data and see if the observations is true.

In [14]:
# Add 2 more columns after separating the mileage variable.

km_per_unit_fuel = []
mileage_unit = []

for observation in df["Mileage"]:
    if isinstance(observation, str):
        if (
            observation.split(" ")[0]
            .replace(".", "", 1)
            .isdigit()  # first element must be numeric
            and " " in observation  # space between numeric and unit
            and (
                observation.split(" ")[1]
                == "kmpl"  # units are "km/kg" and "kmpl"
                or observation.split(" ")[1] == "km/kg"
            )
        ):
            km_per_unit_fuel.append(float(observation.split(" ")[0]))
            mileage_unit.append(observation.split(" ")[1])
        else:
            # Find out are there any observations do not follow the column. not follow
            # The required format [number + ' ' + 'km/kg' or 'kmpl']
            print(
                "The data needs further processing. All values are not similar ",
                observation,
            )
    else:
        # If there are any missing values in the mileage column,
        # Than add related missing values to the 2 new columns
        km_per_unit_fuel.append(np.nan)
        mileage_unit.append(np.nan)

Observations on Engine¶

The data dictionary recommends that Engine shows the dislocation level of the engine in CC. all the observations must follow the same format so create a new numeric column from this column.

Using a regrex to make all the necessary checks time, and regrex to make all the neccesary checks.

In [18]:
# re module gives backing for usual expressions
import re

# Make a new column after separating the engine valuesion.
engine_number = []

# Regex for numeric + " " + "CC"  format
regex_engine = "^\d+(\.\d+)? CC$"

for observation in df["Engine"]:
    if isinstance(observation, str):
        if re.match(regex_engine, observation):
            engine_number.append(float(observation.split(" ")[0]))
        else:
            # Find out if there are any observations in the column that do not follow [numeric + " " + "CC"]  format
            print(
                "The data needs furthur processing. All values are not similar ",
                observation,
            )
    else:
        # If there are any missing values in the engine column, than add missing values to the new column
        engine_number.append(np.nan)

# sklearn method requires, if we use them for imputation encode categorical variables.
# So we only will select numeric features for imputation

from sklearn.impute import KNNImputer

imputer = KNNImputer(n_neighbors=3, weights="uniform")  # 3 Nearest Neighbours
temp_df_for_imputation = df[["engine_number", "power_number", "Year", "km_per_unit_fuel", "Seats"]]
temp_df_for_imputation = imputer.fit_transform(temp_df_for_imputation)
temp_df_for_imputation = pd.DataFrame(temp_df_for_imputation, 
                                      columns = ["engine_number", "power_number", "Year", "km_per_unit_fuel", "Seats"],
)

# Adding imputed columns to the original dataset
df["power_number"] = temp_df_for_imputation["power_number"]
df["km_per_unit_fuel"] = temp_df_for_imputation["km_per_unit_fuel"]

Nothern = ['Delhi','Jaipur']

Western =['Mumbai', 'Pune','Ahmedabad' ]

Eastern = ['Kolkata' ]

Southern = ['Hyderabad', 'Kochi', 'Coimbatore', 'Chennai', 'Banglore']
In [62]:
### Defining a user function for continents
def Regions(x):
    if x in Nothern:
        return 'North_India'
    elif x in Western:
        return 'West_India'
    elif x in Eastern:
        return 'East_India'
    else:
        return 'South_India'

# Treat outliers by capping and flooring. 
def treat_outliers(df,col):
    '''
    treats outliers in a varaible
    col: str, name of the numerical varaible
    df: data frame
    col: name of the column
    '''
    Q1=df[col].quantile(0.25) # 25th quantile
    Q3=df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR=Q3-Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - 1.5*IQR 
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + 1.5*IQR
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker) # all the values samller than Lower_Whisker will be designated value of Lower_whisker 
                                                            # and all the values bigger upper_whishker will be designated value of upper_Whisker 
    return df

def treat_outliers_all(df, col_list):
    '''
    treat outlier in all numerical varaibles
    col_list: list of numerical varaibles
    df: data frame
    '''
    for c in col_list:
        df = treat_outliers(df,c)
        
    return df

Create Dummy Variables¶

Some values like Mumbai or Pune cannot be read into an equivalence. Using alternatives like 2 for Pune, and 1 for Mumbai, so on would result in inferring several baseless statements which should be escaped. But Owner Type can be given substitutes such as 1 for First owner, 2 for Second Owner.

For the rest of the categorical variables dummy variables are creates and drop first =True is set. If we do not drop one of the dummies, then they become linearly related and violate model assumptions.

import math

# RMSE
def rmse(predictions, targets):
    return np.sqrt(((targets - predictions) ** 2).mean())


# MAE
def mae(predictions, targets):
    return np.mean(np.abs((targets - predictions)))


# Model Performance on train and test data
def model_pref(olsmodel, x_train, x_test):

    # Insample Prediction
    y_pred_train_pricelog = olsmodel.predict(x_train)
    y_pred_train_Price = y_pred_train_pricelog.apply(math.exp)
    y_train_Price = y_train["Price_log"]

    # Prediction on test data
    y_pred_test_pricelog = olsmodel.predict(x_test)
    y_pred_test_Price = y_pred_test_pricelog.apply(math.exp)
    y_test_Price = y_test["Price_log"]

    print(
        pd.DataFrame(
            {
                "Data": ["Train", "Test"],
                "RMSE": [
                    rmse(y_pred_train_Price, y_train_Price),
                    rmse(y_pred_test_Price, y_test_Price),
                ],
                "MAE": [
                    mae(y_pred_train_Price, y_train_Price),
                    mae(y_pred_test_Price, y_test_Price),
                ], 
                 
                
            }
        )
    )
    

#Check model performance
model_pref(ols model1, x_train, x_test)

from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor


def checking_vif(train):
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["feature"] = train.columns

    # calculating VIF for each feature
    vif["VIF"] = [
        variance_inflation_factor(train.values, i) for i in range(len(train.columns))
    ]
    return vif

Removing Multicollinearity¶

In [164]:
 
def treating_multicollinearity(high_vif_columns, x_train, x_test):
    """
    Drop every column that has VIF score greater than 5, one by one.
    Look at the adjusted R square of all these models
    Look at the RMSE of all these models on test data
    """
    adj_rsq_scores = []
    rmse_test_data = []

    # build ols models with dropping one of these at a time and observe the Adjusted R-squared
    for cols in high_vif_columns:
        train = x_train.loc[:, ~x_train.columns.str.startswith(cols)]
        test = x_test.loc[:, ~x_test.columns.str.startswith(cols)]
        # Create the model
        olsres = build_ols_model(train)
        # Adj R-Sq
        adj_rsq_scores.append(olsres.rsquared_adj)
        # RMSE (Test data)
        y_pred_test_pricelog = olsres.predict(test)
        y_pred_test_Price = y_pred_test_pricelog.apply(math.exp)
        y_test_Price = y_test["Price_log"]
        rmse_test_data.append(rmse(y_pred_test_Price, y_test_Price))

    # Add new Adj_Rsq and RMSE after dropping each colmn
    temp = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "col": high_vif_columns,
            "Adj_rsq_after_dropping_col": adj_rsq_scores,
            "Test RMSE": rmse_test_data,
        }
    ).sort_values(by="Adj_rsq_after_dropping_col", ascending=False)

    print(temp)
    print("\n\n")

Observations from the model¶

Observation¶

With our linear regression model we have been able to capture ~90 variation in our data.

The model indicates that the most significant predictors of price of used cars are -

The year of manufacturing

Number of seats in the car

Power of the engine

Mileage

Kilometers Driven

Location

Fuel_Type

Transmission - Automatic/Manual

Car Category - budget brand to ultra luxury The p-values for these predictors are <0.05 in our final model

Newer cars sell for higher prices. 1 unit increase in the year of manufacture leads to [ exp(0.1170) = 1.12 Lakh ] increase in the price of the vehicle, when everything else is constant. It is important to note here that the predicted values are log(price) and therefore coefficients have to converted accordingly to understand that influence in Price.

As the number of seats increases, the price of the car increases - exp(0.0343) = 1.03 Lakhs

Mileage is inversely correlated with Price. Generally, high Mileage cars are the lower budget cars. It is important to note here that correlation is not equal to causation. That is to say that increase in Mileage does not lead to a drop in prices. It can be understood in such a way that the cars with high mileage do not have a high power engine and therefore have low prices.

Kilometers Driven have a negative relationship with the price which is intuitive. A car that has been driven more will have more wear and tear and hence sell at a lower price, everything else being 0.

The categorical variables are a little hard to interpret. But it can be seen that all the car_category variables in the dataset have a positive relationship with the Price and the magnitude of this positive relationship increases as the brand category moves to the luxury brands. It will not be incorrect to interpret that the dropped car_category variable for budget friendly cars would have a negative relationship with the price (because the other 3 are increasingly positive.)

Recommendation¶

1.Year is positive correlated with Price: So New car is more valuable. 2.Price and Kilometers has negative correlation: So, Les milage cars are more valuable. 3.Manual cars price has shown a smooth incline over the time: So manual car is less valuable.

4.Petrol and Diesel used cars price show a continual increase. But Diesel cars are more expensive than Petrol cars. So, prefer diesel cars over petrol cars. 5.The price for electric cars is constant across the years: Soon electric cars is more valuable.

6.Automatic Firsthand cars have a greater price in comparison than others: So, prefer firsthand car is better. 7.Mumbai has the maximum selling and buying used cars, and the minimum is in Ahmedabad. but the same split seen for Puna, Coimbatore, and Kochi, and for Jaipur and Kolkata. Mumbai is best area for this business: For new business Mumbai is best region.
